<font color="#FF0000">DON'T GO BACK TO MEMORY LANE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 10 22:17:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward, by the way, sorry to call you Edmond. I have thought about your questions all day today. I can't give you a clean answer.  What was real and intense to me as a 18 or 20 year old is gone, what I have now is a 52 year old trying to reconstruct memories.  <br><br>
I went up into the loft in my garage and dug out my old draft board war box. Filled with letters between the Board and Me, and I read what I wrote on my Application for Conscientious Objector Status. It's a 4 page green form, of which you attached tons of pages and testimony from others. It was a long and painful trip down memory lane, but it left me feeling empty and frustrated.  I think the old axiom about youth being wasted on the young may apply here.<br><br>
Before I became a war protestor, I was very active in Civil Rights (even spent an evening with M.L.King Jr), but now the flames of civil rights do not burn bright within me. Too many riots, Rodney Kings, Crips &amp; Bloods, and assorted crime stats.  Perhaps idealism is what drove me back then, and reality is what drives me now. I just don't know.<br><br>
On a factual level I know now, in 1997, that the war in Viet Nam was wrong, as well as Watergate, etc. But now I am so much older, I was younger then that then.  I sat up in the garage loft, with the sweat running down my face, and read words that I knew I wrote, long ago, but words that I had trouble believing in today.  (Is that honest enough for you Arthur?). Back then I also believed Arabs and Jews could live together in peace, now I don't.<br><br>
I would not change what I did for one instant. I am still proud of every protest, every demostration. Every draft card I burned.  What good it did, now I can question. Did we give aid and comfort to the &quot;enemy&quot; or did we help end the murder of American lads a bit quicker? And Vietnamese lads, and women, and children too. Who is without sin to cast that first stone?<br><br>
You, and almost I, were called upon to serve our country. I choose a different path. Others choose to leave and go North to Canada. Others choose to do nothing and went to VietNam. Now the Vietnamese live with us, and their kids are learning how to be Americans, complete with home invasion robberies and drive-by shootings.  <br><br>
Damn Ed, What we had with Chevys and Fords pales in comparison with the horrors that came upon us.  What innocence we had, what a luxury.  Do you think if we had been born in Saigon after WW2 we would even know what a Ford or a Chevy was?  Man, I am more confused than ever, now, having taken this E ticket ride down memory lane.  I hope others can relate to this too.<br><br>
If this is typical of the questions you ask when you are not name calling, please go back to Wharf Rat (:-) or car parts, this is too much of a head banger.
